          "value":
              "• Researchers at Harvard Business School conducted a study to explore whether an individual's body language could affect people's opinion of that person, as Van Edwards explains in his Udemy.com class. Turns out, this is what the research found.\n\nLight body language, the body is normally contracted, with the shoulders and head pointing down or tilted.\n\nHigh intensity body language is expansive. The head is held high, the arms are loose, the shoulders are set back and the chest is out. By expressing powerful body language, you are seen as more influential. High intensity body language not only affects the way others see you, but also the way you see yourself."
